<subSubSection pageNumber="820" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="820">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="820">Note:</emphasis>
Webb argued that the only possible original element is 575.37 (LINN), annotated as &quot;15 aspera&quot; by Linnaeus, but from Siberia, where 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Saxifragaceae" genus="Saxifraga" kingdom="Plantae" order="Saxifragales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aspera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="820">S. aspera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not occur (and for which Linnaeus indicated a European origin), suggesting that Linnaeus probably omitted to change his annotation when he decided to recognise this as a separate species. Holmgren &amp; Holmgren (
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="820">Intermountain Fl.</emphasis>
3A: 56. 1997) accepted this, noting that 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Webbâ€™s">Webb's</normalizedToken>
choice supersedes the 
<typeStatus>neotype</typeStatus>
choice made by Siplivinsky (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="820">Novosti Sist. Vyssh. Rast.</emphasis>
8: 149. 1971).
</paragraph>
